Reference

Defining your model

Parameter estimation and dose recommendation needs a model. The methods below allow you to construct a model using nlmixr, RxODE, deSolve or algebraic equations.

algebraic()

Use an external function to generate an algebraic model, capable of being used with tdmore() Algebraic functions are assumed to be dose-linear, meaning that they can be calculated for a single dose and then summed up for multiple doses.

tdmore()

tdmore is a generic function to append TDM functionality to a pharmacometrics model.

tdmore(<algebraic>)

Build a tdmore object based on an algebraic model

tdmore(<default>)

Default function, catching unsupported types of models

tdmore(<nlmixrUI>)

Create a TDM-capable model from an nlmixr UI object.

tdmore(<nlmixrFitCore>)

Create a TDM-capable model from an nlmixr result.

tdmore(<RxODE>)

Create a TDM-capable model from an RxODE model

tdmore_deSolve()

Create a TDM-capable model from a deSolve model

errorModel()

Instantiate a new error model.

print(<tdmore>)

Print a tdmore object.

summary(<tdmore>)

Summarise a tdmore object.

Simulating from the model

TDMore offers a single unifying interface to simulate from a model.

predict(<tdmore>)

Predict from a tdmore model

model.frame(<tdmore>)

Get the specified data values, with the upper and lower bounds provided by the residual error model

residuals(<tdmorefit>) residuals(<tdmore>)

Get the residuals for a specific tdmorefit

Estimating individual parameters

Use this simple command to estimate individual parameters. This results in a tdmorefit object. You can also define your own tdmorefit object with fixed parameter estimates.

estimate()

Calculate the Empirical Bayesian Estimate parameters that predict a given dataset using the model

tdmorefit()

Create a tdmorefit object manually

fitted(<tdmorefit>)

Get the predicted (fitted) data

formula(<tdmorefit>)

Get the model used to provide this fit

logLik(<tdmorefit>)

Calculate the log-likelihood of the predicted values. If fixed values were used to obtain the tdmorefit, they are considered estimated and are included in the population log-likelihood.

model.frame(<tdmorefit>)

Get the observed values used to provide this model fit.

predict(<tdmorefit>)

Predict new data using the current model

print(<tdmorefit>)

Print an EBE fit.

summary(<tdmorefit>)

Summary of a tdmorefit object.

coef(<tdmorefit>)

The obtained parameter values for the fit

vcov(<tdmorefit>)

The variance-covariance matrix

confint(<tdmorefit>)

Calculates the confidence interval on the obtained parameter values

Investigate the log-likelihood profile

Get more information about the log-likelihood profile, how it looks like, and why a certain parameter set was estimated.

profile(<tdmorefit>)

Get an overview of the log-likelihood for varying parameter values. If arguments `fix` and `limits` are not set for a specific parameter, individual eta's will be generated to cover 95 percent of the population distribution.

getLikelihoodFun()

Get the right likelihood function for the specified type.

ll()

Calculate the log likelihood as the sum of the population likelihood and the prediction likelihood.

pop_ll()

Calculate the population log likelihood. Fixed values are ignored.

pred_ll()

Calculate the prediction log likelihood. Fixed values are appended to the provided parameter estimate

Plotting

We offer many plotting functions, all based on ggplot2. We suggest you build a ggplot object using ggplot.tdmorefit(), allowing you to do things like ggplot(myFit) + stat_predict().

addIterationColumn()

Add an iteration column 'ITER' to the observed dataframe. The iteration column determines in which MPC iteration each observation will be included.

algebraic()

Use an external function to generate an algebraic model, capable of being used with tdmore() Algebraic functions are assumed to be dose-linear, meaning that they can be calculated for a single dose and then summed up for multiple doses.

as.RxODE_regimen()

Add the given regimen into the RxODE event table.

as.population()

Transform a tdmore fit object into a population fit This is done by re-executing the 'estimate' function, but with no observed data

autolayer(<recommendation>)

Automatically create the required layers for a recommendation object

autolayer(<tdmorefit>)

Automatically plot a tdmorefit object

autoplot(<tdmore>)

Plot a tdmore object as the population

autoplot(<tdmorefit>)

Plot a tdmorefit object.

autoplot(<tdmorefit_mixture>)

Plot a tdmorefit_mixture object.

coef(<recommendation>)

The obtained parameter values for a recommendation.

coef(<tdmorefit>)

The obtained parameter values for the fit

computeMaxTime()

Compute the maximum interesting time value based on the specified regimen and observed data.

confint(<tdmorefit>)

Calculates the confidence interval on the obtained parameter values

covariate()

Create a new covariate object.

curry_covariate()

Fill in a specific covariate in a model, transforming it into a more specific model.

dataTibble()

Utility function to create a data tibble.

default_model

Default example model TODO: Better documentation required

discrete.searchspace()

Add discrete options to a search space

errorModel()

Instantiate a new error model.

estimate()

Calculate the Empirical Bayesian Estimate parameters that predict a given dataset using the model

estimate(<tdmore_mpc>)

MPC estimate method.

estimateMixtureModel()

Calculate the Empirical Bayesian Estimate parameters that predict a given dataset using a mixture model.

evaluate()

Evaluate all discrete regimen possibilities

expandOmega()

Expand OMEGA matrix by duplicating variance-covariance information for IOV terms. Note that the column and row names of the returned matrix are strictly identical to the ones returned by getParameterNames().

findDose()

Find the dose required (quick and dirty, to be optimised)

findFirstCompatibleModel()

Find the first model in the TDMore set compatible with the specified covariates.

fitted(<tdmorefit>)

Get the predicted (fitted) data

flatten()

Flatten a treatment regimen

fluticasone_model

Default example model TODO: Better documentation required

formula(<tdmorefit>)

Get the model used to provide this fit

formulation()

Create a new formulation object.

fortify(<tdmorefit>)

Convert a tdmorefit object to a data.frame using `model.frame`. The data.frame has a special 'tdmoreArgs' attribute that is used to capture all extra arguments to the original ggplot call. The attribute contains a list with element 'tdmorefit' and all extra named arguments to the fortify call.

getAes()

This function tries to construct an aes by guessing the required variables

getLikelihoodFun()

Get the right likelihood function for the specified type.

getMaxOccasion()

Get the highest occasion number in a regimen. If the regimen does not contain an 'OCC' column, 1 is returned.

getMetadataByClass()

Get metadata by class.

getMetadataByName()

Get metadata (output, formulation or covariate) by name.

getObservedVariables()

Get the observed variables from the tdmore model.

getOccasionTimes()

Get the times related to each occasion in a regimen.

getParameterNames()

Get the parameter names. If IOV is defined in the model, IOV terms will be added at the end of the character array and repeated as many times as there are occasions in the regimen. E.g. 2 occasions: "ECL", "EKA", "ECL_IOV", "EKA_IOV", "ECL_IOV", "EKA_IOV"

getPredictOutputNames()

Return the output names of the fitted MC matrix.

hasOccasion()

Tell if a regimen has an occasion column.

is.mpc()

Test if an object is a `tdmore_mpc` model

is.tdmore()

Test if object is of class `tdmore`

linCmt()

This function guesses which model should be calculated, based on the available variables in the caller environment

ll()

Calculate the log likelihood as the sum of the population likelihood and the prediction likelihood.

logLik(<tdmorefit>)

Calculate the log-likelihood of the predicted values. If fixed values were used to obtain the tdmorefit, they are considered estimated and are included in the population log-likelihood.

mergeCovariates()

Merge covariates.

Create an 'observed variables' object. These variables will be predicted and shown in the panel below the timeline. TODO: discuss if we keep this info as part of the UI metadata of the model. Should we need a config tab to configure the UI metadata? Do we want to persist this information in DB? Per model? Per patient? etc.

Calculate the population log likelihood. Fixed values are ignored.

Calculate all possible regimen combinations, as rows in a data.frame

These functions perform estimate for multiple individuals at the same time.

Calculate the prediction log likelihood. Fixed values are appended to the provided parameter estimate

Predict from a tdmore model

Predict a tdmoreCurried object.

MPC predict method.

predict(<tdmorefit>)

Predict new data using the current model

Predict from a tdmorefit mixture object.

predictionLayer()

This creates a special type of ggplot2 Layer object. The layer searches for a tdmorefit object in either the plot, or its own arguments. It then calls the `predict()` function and provides this data.frame instead of the original data

Print a recommendation object.

Print a tdmore object.

Print a tdmoreCurried object.

Print an EBE fit.

processParameters()

Check input parameters and return a standardised named num array with the parameter names and values. If the initial values are not provided, zeroes will be used (=population values for ETAS) Provided parameters will overwrite initial values.

profile(<tdmorefit>)

Get an overview of the log-likelihood for varying parameter values. If arguments `fix` and `limits` are not set for a specific parameter, individual eta's will be generated to cover 95 percent of the population distribution.

residuals(<tdmorefit>) residuals(<tdmore>)

Get the residuals for a specific tdmorefit

roundTime()

For a given set of planned times, round to the nearest reference time.

sampleMC()

Generate parameter samples using uncertainty around the fit.

sampleMC_metrop()

Generate parameter samples using the Metropolis MCMC method.

sampleMC_norm()

Generate parameter samples using a muilti-variate normal distribution around the variance-covariance matrix

searchspace()

Define a blank search space

Summarise fitted MC matrix over all the samples. TIME column must be present.

tdmore_set()

Create a TDMore set. Note that the order of the given models matters. Order must be defined from the most restrictive model (with a high number of covariates) to the lowest restrictive model (with a low number of covariates). These models will be tried one by one from left to right with the 'observed' data. The first model matching the covariates from the 'observed' data will be used.
